   <note>French-Swiss Auguste Burnand (ca. 1835-1860?), who lived in a small Swiss colony in the vicinity of Knoxville from 1853-1860, is the creator of these sketches. His sketchbook of pencil drawings, done in 1855 and 1856, occasionally with a watercolor wash includes scenes of the houses, social life and working life in the area of Knox County. It also includes the oldest surviving drawings of several Knoxville houses, including those of prominent persons, and of local landmarks.</note>
